ve.org/web/20191201200009/https://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.4255/title.the-20-best-rap-albums-of-all-time-from-artists-who-just-happen-to-be-women|archivedate=December 1, 2019|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/xxx-hip-hop-mw0000571888|title=AllMusic Review by Tim Sendra|last=Sendra|first=Tim|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923121202/http://www.allmusic.com/album/xxx-hip-hop-mw0000571888|archivedate=September 23, 2017|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last1=Buckley|editor-first1=Peter|last=Shapiro|first=Peter|author-link=Peter Shapiro (journalist)|title=The Rough Guide to Rock|year=2003|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|location=|isbn=9781843531050|url=https://archive.org/details/roughguidetorock0003unse|ref=harv|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259639459/|url-access=subscription|title=Just don't call me a wuss|last=Sullivan|first=Caroline|date=July 27, 2001|work=[[The Guardian]]|page=66|access-date=December 1, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]|ref=harv}} {{subscription required}}\n* {{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|author-link=Joel Whitburn|title=Joel Whitburn Presents Top R & B/hip-hop Singles, 1942-2004|year=2004|publisher=Record Research Incorporated|location=|isbn=9780898201604|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Joel_Whitburn_Presents_Top_R_B_hip_hop_S/bZozAQAAIAAJ?hl=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite episode|title=Some Assembly Required|series=[[Dark Angel (2000 TV series)|Dark Angel]]|author=Writer: [[Robert Doherty (writer)|Robert Doherty]]. Director: [[Nick Marck]].|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]]|season=2|airdate=November 16, 2001|ref={{sfnref|''Dark Angel''|2001}}}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|foxy-brown|candy}}\n\n{{Foxy Brown}}\n{{Kelis}}\n\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Dance-pop songs]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n[[Category:Foxy Brown (rapper) songs]]\n[[Category:Kelis songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by The Neptunes]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chad Hugo]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Foxy Brown (rapper)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Pharrell Williams]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name           = Candy\n| type           = single\n| cover          = Foxy Brown Candy.jpg\n| artist         = [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]] featuring [[Kelis]]\n| album          = [[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]\n| alt            = An image of a black woman wearing a pink swimsuit while sitting in front of a pink background. The song title and artists' names are included on the image.\n| B-side         = \"730\"\n| released       = August 21, 2001\n| format         = {{flatlist|\n* [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n* [[CD single]]\n}}\n| genre          =\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n<!--Sourced in the \"Composition\" section-->\n| length         = 3:45\n| label          = [[Def Jam]]\n| writer         =\n* Inga Marchand\n* [[Pharrell Williams]]\n* [[Chad Hugo]]\n| producer       = [[The Neptunes]]\n| chronology     = [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]]\n| prev_title     = [[Oh Yeah (Foxy Brown song)|Oh Yeah]]\n| prev_year      = 2001\n| next_title     = [[Stylin']]\n| next_year      = 2002\n}}\n\n\"'''Candy'''\" is a song recorded by American rapper [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]] for her third studio album [[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|''Broken Silence'']] (2001). It was written by Brown and its producers [[The Neptunes]]. [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]] released the song as the album's third single on August&nbsp;21, 2001. \"Candy\" is a [[dance-pop]], [[Pop music|pop]], and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song with [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[1980s music]] influences. American singer [[Kelis]] performs the [[Hook (music)|hook]] while Brown [[Rapping|raps]] the [[Verse (music)|verses]]. The lyrics about [[cunnilingus]]; critics noted that its sexual content contrasted with ''Broken Silence''<nowiki/>'s focus on more introspective topics.\n\nThe song was well received during its release and in retrospective reviews; critics compared it to music by other artists, including [[Lil' Kim]]. Its depiction of black female sexuality attracted attention from academic scholars. The song peaked at number&nbsp;24 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' chart]]. It was featured on featured on soundtracks in the early 2000s, and was played on the television show [[Dark Angel (2000 TV series)|''Dark Angel'']] and the films ''[[Friday After Next]]'' and ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]''.\n\n== Production and release ==\n[[File:Foxy brown-03-mika.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Left side portrait of Foxy Brown looking slightly toward the camera |Foxy Brown (''pictured in 1998'') was a co-writer for \"Candy\".]]\n[[The Neptunes]] produced two songs\u2014\"Candy\" and \"Gangsta Boogie\"\u2014for [[Foxy Brown (rapper)|Foxy Brown]]'s third studio album [[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|''Broken Silence'']] (2001).{{Sfn|''Broken Silence''|2001}}{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001a|p=130}} They co-wrote it with Brown who is credited under her legal name Inga Marchand.{{Sfn|''Broken Silence''|2001}} According to [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s Colin Finan, The Neptunes were so prolific in 2001 that they had \"laced nearly every [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]/[[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] hit\" released that summer.{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} \"Candy\" features vocals by [[Kelis]], a frequent collaborator with the Neptunes.{{Sfn|''Broken Silence''|2001}}{{sfn|Shapiro|2003|p=554}} Music journalist [[Peter Shapiro (journalist)|Peter Shapiro]] wrote that Kelis had become their \"diva of choice\" to sing [[Hook (music)|hook]]s on other artists' songs and noted the diversity of her work mentioning her contributions to music \"for everyone from Foxy Brown to [[Noreaga]]\".{{sfn|Shapiro|2003|p=554}} \"Candy\" was [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] at the Master Sound Recording Studios in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]]. The vocals were recorded by David Hummel and Erik Steinert and [[Audio mixing|mixed]] by Axel Niehaus at Avatar Studios in New York City.{{Sfn|''Broken Silence''|2001}}\n\nThe song debuted at the ''Broken Silence'' listening party held in New York City in June 2001. It was one of several songs, including \"A Letter\" and \"Oh Yeah\", played at the event.{{sfn|Nomatazele|2001}} [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]] released \"Candy\" in the US as the album's third single on August&nbsp;21, 2001,{{Sfn|AllMusic}}{{sfn|Graham|2012}} and [[PolyGram]] promoted it in the UK in 2002.{{Sfn|AllMusic}} The song was issued as a [[12-inch single]] and a [[CD single]];{{Sfn|AllMusic}}{{sfn|WorldCat}} the 12-inch single included the song's [[radio edit]] and [[instrumental]] and \"730\", a track from ''Broken Silence'', as its [[b-side]].{{sfn|WorldCat}}  [[Elektra Records|Elektra]] produced a pink [[vinyl record]] in a limited edition.{{sfn|Whitburn|2004|p=317}} To promote \"Candy\", Brown performed a portion of it in the music video for her single \"Tables Will Turn\".{{sfn|YouTube}} \n\nFollowing its release, \"Candy\" was often featured on early 2000's soundtracks,{{sfn|McDermott|2017}} appearing in the films ''[[Friday After Next]]'' (2002) and ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]'' (2005).{{sfn|''Friday After Next''|2002}}{{sfn|''AFI Catalog of Feature Films''}} Along with its inclusion on the 2002 soundtrack for the television show [[Dark Angel (American TV series)|''Dark Angel'']],{{sfn|Bichmeier}} it was also played in the season two episode \"Some Assembly Required\".{{sfn|''Dark Angel''|2001}} The song was a part of the 2003 [[compilation album]] ''XXX Hip Hop''. [[AllMusic]]'s Tim Sendra wrote that \"Candy\", along with [[Lil' Kim]]'s \"[[The Notorious K.I.M.|Suck My Dick]]\" and [[Khia]]'s \"[[My Neck, My Back (Lick It)]]\", represented the \"nasty females\" on the album.{{sfn|Sendra}}\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{Listen\n|filename=FoxyBrownCandyAudioSample.ogg\n|title=\"Candy\"\n|description=\"Candy\" contains influences from [[new wave music]] and [[1980s music|1980's music]], and its composition incorporates a Spanish guitar.{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001a|p=130}}{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001b|p=110}}{{sfn|Reid|2001}}\n}}\nBrown adopted a \"more [[Pop music|pop]]-influenced\" sound for \"Candy\" compared to that of her previous albums,{{sfn|Fonseca|2019|pp=61-62}} and ''[[HipHopDX]]''{{'}}s Nomatazele further defined its style as [[dance-pop]].{{sfn|Nomatazele|2001}} In [[MTV News]], Shaheem Reid characterized the song as a \"sugary party track\".{{sfn|Reid|2001}} While writer Anthony J. Fonseca described \"Candy\" as a [[Dance music|dance]] song with a pop [[refrain]],{{sfn|Fonseca|2019|pp=61-62}} Colin Finan reviewed it as part of ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s R&B category.{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} The song includes influences from [[new wave music]] and [[1980s music]].{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001a|p=130}}{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001b|p=110}} The instrumental includes a Spanish guitar,{{sfn|Reid|2001}} and is built on a [[staccato]] beat frequently used by The Neptunes.{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} Brown [[Rapping|raps]] the [[Verse (music)|verses]] \"aggressively\" over a [[tempo|mid-tempo]] beat.{{sfn|Fonseca|2019|pp=61-62}} Finan likened her voice to a \"sexy, husky boom\", and considered Kelis, who sings the hook, to have a more \"high-pitched, childlike sound\".{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} \n\n\"Candy\" is about [[cunnilingus]], as represented in lyrics like \"Let me know when you're ready to eat\".{{sfn|Morrissey|2009}}{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}} Finan summed the song up as \"an ode to [[oral sex]]\".{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} Based on this content, reviewers have likened the track to a \"musical [[striptease]]\" in which Brown boasts of her \"sexual prowess\" with a \"graphic description of her bedroom capabilities\".{{sfn|Hall|2001|p=22}}{{sfn|Jones|2001|p=11}} Although ''Broken Silence'' has a larger focus on introspective subject matters, such as \"The Letter\", about a [[suicide attempt]], critics noted it still featured sexually explicit songs, like \"Candy\", as had been the case on Brown's past albums.{{sfn|Clark|2001|p=51}}{{sfn|Partsch III|2001|p=22}}{{sfn|Opie|2018}} While discussing this difference in style, ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Caroline Sullivan clarified: \"But the sexually provocative Foxy of old isn't completely extinct.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|2001|p=66}}\n\n[[Multiculturalism]] professor Nichole A. Guillory wrote that Brown acts as [[stewardess]] by guiding a man to examine different parts of her body, like her breasts and dark skin, while boasting she tastes \"just like candy\". The lyrics, \"Licking my lips / And adjusting my tits and switching my hips\", focus on Brown's body and her attempt to stimulate the man's interest.{{sfn|Guillory|2009}} Although she invites this anonymous male subject to have sex with lyrics like \"imagine me nude, stretched out\" and \"nipples all out, bent over the sink\",{{sfn|Guillory|2009}} she also warns him: \"When I lay on my stomach and throw my legs back / Y'all niggaz won't know how to act.\"{{sfn|Ogunnaike|2001b|p=110}} In the third verse, Brown takes on more \"sexual agency\" as she raps about being on [[Top (sex position)|top]] and her self-worth.{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}}{{sfn|Guillory|2009}}\n\n<blockquote>I'm real sweet like a candy corn...\"<br />Picture me, t-shirt, no panties on<br />...I'm priceless boy\"{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}}</blockquote>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n[[File:Kelis.jpg|thumb|alt=Kelis pictured singing with her arms raised, a microphone in her left hand standing in front of a drummer | Kelis (''pictured in 2007'') received praise for her performance on \"Candy\".]]\n\"Candy\" received a positive response from critics, several of whom cited it as a highlight of ''Broken Silence'', including ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]], Steve Jones for the [[Gannett News Service]], and the ''[[Associated Press]]''{{'}} Latrice Davis.<ref>{{harvnb|Christgau|2001}}; {{harvnb|Jones|2001|p=11}}; {{harvnb|Davis|2001|p=18}}.</ref> In a review for ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'', Rob Clark praised the song as \"undeniably catchy\".{{sfn|Clark|2001|p=51}} Writing for [[Spin (magazine)|''Spin'']], [[Joshua Clover]] described \"Candy\" as a \"strange brew of threatening, hooky, sexy, creepy, and overwhelming\" vocals, and wrote that the Neptunes represented Brown's \"discreet charm\".{{sfn|Clover|2001|p=133}} In ''Billboard'', Colin Finan said the production complimented Brown and Kelis' voices, however, he questioned the song's appeal to some audiences, specifically those of conservative radio stations, due to its sexual content.{{sfn|Finan|2001|p=18}} In a negative review for the ''[[Phoenix New Times]]'', Bret McCabe criticized Brown for not having a strong enough voice for R&B and [[soul music]].{{sfn|McCabe|2001}}\n\nRetrospective reviews of \"Candy\" have been positive. In a 2012 article for [[The Boombox|''The Boombox'']], Nadine Graham said the song was \"sugary sweet, poppy cut\".{{sfn|Graham|2012}} ''HipHopDX''{{'}}s Dana Scott named ''Broken Silence'' one of the top twenty best albums by a female rapper, citing \"Candy\" as a \"pop-worthy [[earworm]]\" that helped to \"to lighten up the showcase\".{{Sfn|Scott|2019}} [[Fuse (TV channel)|''Fuse'']]{{'}}s Jeff Benjamin included the song on his 2014 [[Spotify]] playlist of the best female collaborations.{{sfn|Benjamin|2014}} Praising \"Candy\" as one of Kelis' top ten collaborations in a 2017 article for ''[[The Fader]]'', Patrick D. McDermott said that its hook was \"stone-cold classic Kelis\" and \"unshakeable, and lightyears ahead of its time\".{{sfn|McDermott|2017}} Mark Marymont, writing for ''[[The News-Press]]'', also enjoyed Kelis' contributions to \"Candy\", and believed she sounded better on duets since she had \"sometimes thin, even whiny vocals\".{{sfn|Marymont|2008|p=73}}\n\nReviewers have compared \"Candy\" to music by other artists, including Lil' Kim.{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}}{{sfn|''The Dallas Morning News''|2001}} [[Gender studies]] scholars Jennifer Esposito and Bettina Love likened the song's candy metaphor to Lil' Kim's \"Kitty Box\" from her 2005 album [[The Naked Truth (Lil' Kim album)|''The Naked Truth'']],{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}} while a contributor for ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' said \"Candy\" was not as provocative as Lil' Kim's music.{{sfn|''The Dallas Morning News''|2001}} In a review of [[Macy Gray]]'s 2001 album [[The Id (album)|''The Id'']], ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s Arion Berger wrote that the song \"Harry\" was a \"sexual boast as bold as\" Brown's single \"Candy\", which he described as \"supremely nasty\".{{sfn|Berger|2001}} Author Roni Sarig praised the Neptune's production on \"Candy\", [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s \"[[Work It Out (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Work It Out]]\", and [[Common (rapper)|Common]]'s \"[[Electric Circus (album)|I Got a Right Ta]]\" as a \"combination of classical soul, [[blues]], and pop bundled with twenty-first century digital mayhem\".{{sfn|Sarig|2007}}\n\n=== Racial analysis ===\n\"Candy\" has also been the subject of some scholarly analysis. According to scholar Doyinsola Faluyi, Brown's appearance on the song's cover represents how some black female rappers focused on their sexuality. This was in contrast to artists like [[Da Brat]] who modeled themselves after \"the dominant fashion in male hip-hop culture\" with a more masculine style.{{sfn|Faluyi|2015|p=447}} The lyrics were discussed by Jennifer Esposito and Bettina Love who believed Brown's boasts about being the dominant partner during sex combated psychologist [[Michelle Fine]]'s theories on \"sexuality as victimization\". Brown's explicit demands for oral sex throughout the song serves to challenge negative cultural attitudes about sexually active women \"mak[ing] it clear that women can desire sex and can ask for pleasure\".{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}}\n\nNichole A. Guillory criticized \"Candy\" as a [[sexual fantasy]] that [[Sexual objectification|objectifies]] a black woman's body to appeal to a [[male gaze]], writing that its lyrics present black women as \"territories to be penetrated, occupied and ravaged by men\". Guillory noted Brown demonstrates some agency when she brags about being priceless and skilled as a top. Although she felt this moment was not strong enough to undo the overall objectification present in the lyrics, she acknowledged it as \"an important reminder of the ongoing struggle between black women and men for control of black women's bodies\".{{sfn|Guillory|2009}} In another critical analysis of the song, Esposito and Love questioned if Brown was promoting further the idea that \"bad girls are used sexually by men, while good girls are the ones men want to marry\".{{sfn|Esposito|Love|2008|pp=43-44}}\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n\"Candy\" debuted at number 24 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' chart]] on September 15, 2001.{{sfn|''Billboard'' a}} It also peaked at number 48 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] ''Billboard'' chart and number 10 on the [[Hot Rap Songs]] ''Billboard'' chart in September 2001.{{sfn|''Billboard'' b}}{{sfn|''Billboard'' c}} While discussing the song's commercial performance, ''The Boombox's'' Nadine Graham said it was hated by \"the streets\" and it had \"struggled its way up\" the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart.{{sfn|Graham|2012}}\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 12\" single{{sfn|WorldCat}}\n| title1 = Candy\n| note1 = radio edit\n| length1 = 3:45\n| title2 = Candy\n| note2 = LP version\n| length2 = 3:43\n| title3 = Candy\n| note3 = instrumental\n| length3 = 3:43\n| title4 = 730\n| note4 = radio edit\n| length4 = 4:00\n| title5 = 730\n| note5 = LP version\n| length5 = 4:12\n| title6 = 730\n| note6 = instrumental\n| length6 = 4:11\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Broken Silence''.{{Sfn|''Broken Silence''|2001}}\n\n'''Recording locations'''\n* Master Sound Recording Studios (Virginia Beach)\n* Avatar Studios (New York City)\n\n'''Personnel'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* Featuring&nbsp;\u2013 Kelis\n* Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Axel Niehaus\n* Producer&nbsp;\u2013 The Neptunes\n{{col-2}}\n* Recording&nbsp;\u2013 David Hummel\n* Vocal recording&nbsp;\u2013 Erik Steinert\n* Composition&nbsp;\u2013 C. Hugo, I. Marchand, P. Williams\n{{col-2}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2001)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]){{sfn|''Billboard'' a}}\n| 24\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]){{sfn|''Billboard'' b}}\n| 48\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot Rap Songs]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]){{sfn|''Billboard'' c}}\n| 10\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Refbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/54473|title=The 40 Year Old Virgin (2005)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529072645/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/54473|archivedate=May 29, 2019|url-status=live|ref={{sfnref|''AFI Catalog of Feature Films''}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.fuse.tv/2014/05/female-collaborations-playlist|title=35 Fiery Female Collaborations From Iggy & Ariana to Mariah & Whitney|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|date=May 7, 2014|publisher=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209065343/http://www.fuse.tv/2014/05/female-collaborations-pl